          <div class="copy-content">
<strong>Lesson 5: Passive Transport (No Energy Required)</strong>

<strong>Simple Diffusion:</strong>
‚Ä¢ Movement of small, nonpolar molecules (O‚ÇÇ, CO‚ÇÇ, lipids)
‚Ä¢ Directly through phospholipid bilayer
‚Ä¢ Down concentration gradient (high ‚Üí low)
‚Ä¢ Rate factors: gradient steepness, temperature, surface area, thickness

<strong>Facilitated Diffusion:</strong>
‚Ä¢ Uses membrane proteins (channels or carriers)
‚Ä¢ For large or charged molecules (glucose, ions, water via aquaporins)
‚Ä¢ Still passive (no ATP)
‚Ä¢ Down concentration gradient
‚Ä¢ Saturable (limited by number of proteins)

<strong>Key Differences:</strong>
‚Ä¢ Simple: No proteins, fast for small molecules
‚Ä¢ Facilitated: Requires proteins, specific/selective
‚Ä¢ Both: Passive, down gradient, no energy

<strong>Why it matters:</strong>
‚Ä¢ Oxygen enters cells, CO‚ÇÇ exits
‚Ä¢ Glucose enters cells for respiration
‚Ä¢ Water balance (osmosis - next lesson)
‚Ä¢ CFTR defect = cystic fibrosis (clinical link)
